The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Noida, Oct. 19 (PTI): A 28-year-old BPO employee was found dead today in a church guest house in Noida, police said.           
	The body of Conrad Dominic Xavier, who had been living in the guest house in Sector 27 for over a year, was found in a pool of blood in his room by a church employee. A cook who lives on the second floor of the guest house is being interrogated.                   
	 Chandigarh (PTI): Harbhajan Singh has apologised for appearing on a TV show dressed as Ravana. Harbhajan, who earned the wrath of th e Sikh community, said: I apologise if my actions have hurt anybody. It was not my intention to hurt the sentiments of anyone which includes members of my own community.                  
	 Bhopal (PTI): A godman in Bhopal was charged with rape on Saturday on the basis of a complaint by an engineering student. Lal Sai allegedly drugged and raped the girl in his ashram in Bairagarh.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court has rejected a petition by an army officer accused of supplying unhygienic meat to troops. Lt Col S.S. Shekhavat had challenged the Censure of Severe Displeasure passed by the defence ministry in July 2003.                   
	 Srinagar (PTI): Security has been tightened along the recently inaugurated 66km train route in Kashmir after a series of hoax calls threatened a terror attack, authorities said. Security forces guarding under-construction railway tracks between Qazigund and Anantnag, and between Baramulla and Rajwansher, have been alerted.                   
	 Rameswaram (PTI): The Coastal Security Police on Sunday asked fishermen to carry identity cards issued by the fisheries department while venturing into the sea and not to cross the Indian maritime border. The fishermen have been asked to paint their boats orange and write the registration number on it.                                                                                                                         
